hands_on_practices.problem:
An outer-sphere electron transfer reaction occurs between hexaammineruthenium(III), $[\text{Ru}(\text{NH}_3)_6]^{3+}$, and cobalt(II) sepulchrate, $[\text{Co}(\text{sep})]^{2+}$, in an aqueous solution under standard conditions. The sepulchrate (sep) ligand is a macrobicyclic encapsulating ligand designed to prevent inner-sphere mechanisms. The standard reduction potentials for the relevant half-reactions are provided below:
$$
\begin{aligned}
[\text{Ru}(\text{NH}_3)_6]^{3+} + e^{-} &\rightleftharpoons [\text{Ru}(\text{NH}_3)_6]^{2+}, \quad E^{\circ} = +0.10 \text{ V} \\
[\text{Co}(\text{sep})]^{3+} + e^{-} &\rightleftharpoons [\text{Co}(\text{sep})]^{2+}, \quad E^{\circ} = -0.28 \text{ V}
\end{aligned}
$$
Calculate the standard Gibbs free energy change, $\Delta G^{\circ}$, for the reaction between $[\text{Ru}(\text{NH}_3)_6]^{3+}$ and $[\text{Co}(\text{sep})]^{2+}$. Use the value of the Faraday constant, $F = 96485 \text{ C/mol}$. Express your answer in kilojoules per mole (kJ/mol), rounded to three significant figures.
